{"key":"post-12514508","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12514508</id>\n<content>Don't worry too much about the grains, because it doesn't matter if they glow brightly or not.&amp;nbsp; If you'll make your substrate with hardwoods, the pH will be very close to where you want it without testing.&amp;nbsp; Add a bit of rice, wheat or oat bran to the substrate, but skip the gypsum.&amp;nbsp; Your pH will be about 6 at the start, but will drop to around 4 shortly after full colonization due to enzymes secreted by the fungus.&amp;nbsp; You won't need much citric acid.&amp;nbsp; I wouldn't use more than a tablespoon in a filter patch bag of sawdust.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you decide to soak the substrate to initiate fruiting, soak it in water adjusted to pH 4, which is easy to measure with litmus strips.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12514547</next>\n<prev>12514426</prev>\n<first>12506702</first>\n<last>13733959</last>\n<when>1273126647</when>\n<utime>05/06/10 09:17 AM</utime>\n</post>"}